Nominal Comparison
==================
Goal:
To compare quantitative values for one or more categories.


Design solutions:
* sub-categories -> color encoded columns or bars
* many categories -> small-multiples / series
* few categories & many items -> bar chart
* few categories & few items -> column chart

Example:
// categories
var simple = category('Sales', 'Engineering', 'Marketing');
simple.data(10, 12, 8);

// categories with sub categories
var bonds = category('Treasury Bonds', 'AAA Municipal Bonds');
var years = category('Two-Year Yields', 'Ten-Year Yields');
years.data(bonds.data(1.1, 3), bonds.data(3.1, 5.7));


Time series
===========
Goal:
To display a relationship between quantitative values belonging to one or more categories and subdivisions of time.

Design solutions:
* few time subdivisions & many categories -> line chart with a line for each category
* few time subdivisions & few categories -> column chart
* many time subdivisions -> line chart

Example:
var d = category('Sales', 'Engineering');
var t = time(2001, 2002, 2003, 2004);
t.data(
	d.data(2, 2.2), // 2001
	d.data(3, 5),   // 2002
	d.data(1, 5),   // 2003
	d.data(10, 2)   // 2004
);

Part-to-Whole (Composition)
===========================


Distribution
============
Goal:
To display the distribution of quantitative values over a range.

Design solutions:
* single variable & few values -> histogram
	- var data =  [1, 3, 3, 4, 7, 5, 3, 2, 1];
	- var label = 
* single variable & many values -> line histogram
* two variables -> scatter chart

var v = Variable(1);
v.data(1, 3, 3, 4, 7, 5, 3, 2, 1);

var v = Variable(2);
v.data(
	[1, 1],
	[2, 1],
	[2, 1],
	[1, 3],
	[2, 1]
);

Correlation
===========
Goal:
To display the correlation between a set of quantitative values.

Design solutions:
* two variables -> scatter chart
	var data = [
		Category(name, []),
		Category(name, [])
	];

	var data = [
		[10, 12],
		[11, 9],
		[15, 8]
	];
* three variables -> bubble chart
	var data = [
		[10, 12, 3],
		[11, 9, 2],
		[15, 9, 4]
	];

----------------------------------------------------------------
categories (categories are nominal and unordered---although visually we would like to have a consistent order)
sub categories
quantitative values
time subdivisions (time is an ordered set of categories)

Basic data types:
Category([string]).data([number|data]) -> data
Time([year]).data([number|data]) -> data
Variable(number).data([number]) -> data

Other data types to consider:
range / intervals
functions














